WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:04.000
Hi everyone. I have a question for you.

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:06.000
Have you ever seen a graph and thought to yourself,

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:09.000
how am I going to recreate this?

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Right? That's what I thought the first time I saw

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:16.000
W. E. B. Du Bois' 1900 Paris Exposition Charts.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:19.000
They're intricate, they're bold, they're colorful,

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:22.000
and they tell more than just a story.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:26.000
They tell more than the numbers, but the people behind the numbers.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:29.000
But historical visualizations are like that.

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:32.000
They teach clarity over constraint.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:39.000
That is, they show you how to focus and foster on creativity, efficiency.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:44.000
They narrow down efforts and decision making.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:49.000
Take Charles Menard's 1921's cartographic depiction

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:55.000
of Napoleon's disastrous Russian march into Russia,

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:59.000
which comprises and compresses multiple dimensions

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:05.000
of the impact of the winter, dates, longitude, latitude, and the troops.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:10.000
All in one graphic, without losing its clarity.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:14.000
O'Florian Nightingale's coxcomb diagram,

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:19.000
which not only shows how really the soldiers died

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:22.000
during the Crimean 1957 war,

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:26.000
but the reality that they died not from bullet wounds,

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:29.000
but from the squalor conditions they got

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:31.000
because of the preventable diseases.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:38.000
The policy from this chart changed and created the nursing profession.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:43.000
O'William Playwright's 1912's plot depicting

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:48.000
the quarter price of wheat as well as the paid labor.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:51.000
Not only was it the foundation for statistical depiction,

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:55.000
but also showed national and economic debt,

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:58.000
as well as trade balances.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:03.000
Now, recreating Dubois' revolutionary charts

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:08.000
showed that you can actually create a checklist of reproducible design.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:11.000
And when you follow that checklist in your own visualizations,

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:15.000
it goes to show that when you plot way

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:17.000
and how you plot your visual elements,

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:21.000
you can actually create your own creative visuals,

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:24.000
which makes it easier for people to see.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:26.000
And when it makes it easier for people to see,

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:29.000
they read faster, they understand what you're trying to say,

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:34.000
and it also makes you a better data visualist.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:37.000
And if you follow that checklist again and again and again,

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:40.000
you can get better feedback,

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:44.000
and you can also get people understanding you are better.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:47.000
So we've probably seen this man's image before,

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:49.000
but we have absolutely no idea who he is.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:52.000
Can we tell who he is? Have we seen him before?

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:57.000
William Edward Bogart Dubois, or Dubois as he would like to be called,

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:01.000
was born in Massachusetts in 1968,

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:04.000
and he lived and he worked as a scholar,

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:07.000
a civil rights activist, a historian,

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:10.000
and he actually worked at Clark Atlanta University,

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:14.000
just southwest outside downtown.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:18.000
His life spanned from the American Reconstruction

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:23.000
to the Civil Rights Movement when he died in Ghana in 1963

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:26.000
at the age of 95.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:32.000
So the original data visualizations and captions that he used himself

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:36.000
depict a time that he used to refer to a certain demographic.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:38.000
So I hope no one will be offended.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:41.000
It's just for our edification.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:45.000
So what made the charts unique?

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:49.000
Actually, at the time in his tenure at Clark Atlanta University,

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:53.000
him and his students handcrafted 60 charts.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:56.000
Some of them are on the screen there.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:00.000
What they did was to actually show the black American progress

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:03.000
from the enslavement to where they actually moved

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:05.000
from where they were staying,

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:08.000
the property they owned, the livestock, the land,

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:12.000
and not only were they unique like that,

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:15.000
but they were actually written in English and French by Dubois

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:17.000
because he was actually bilingual,

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:21.000
to appease to the French audience.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:25.000
So what also was unique about them was the layout.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:29.000
Some of the layout was unique because some of the graphs,

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:34.000
as we can see there, were designed in different shapes and styles,

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:39.000
and they were put together in the same space.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:42.000
The narrative were actually put on the graph

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:44.000
to give some context to the data,

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:47.000
to explain to the people what exactly was going on.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:49.000
And not only did he use narrative,

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:53.000
he also used different fonts for the topography

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:57.000
to actually guide the reader to what was going on.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:04:59.000
There was also the use of bold colors.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:02.000
He liked using what they call the pan-African colors,

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:04.000
black, red, white, green, yellow,

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:06.000
and they were bold and vivid

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:11.000
and also drew people to what he wanted to make the point on.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:13.000
So I actually used these three elements,

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:19.000
the narrative, the layout, the topography, and the color,

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:24.000
and used them as elements to recreate the design.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:26.000
So putting all the designs together

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:29.000
actually created the reproducible,

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:33.000
actually relived the old visualizations

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:35.000
as part of the reproducible design.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:37.000
And when I talk about reproducible design,

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:40.000
I'm talking about taking a graph

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:42.000
and breaking it into its visual elements,

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:44.000
like we were talking about,

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:47.000
the fonts, the color, the layout,

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:49.000
and putting them together.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:54.000
Step by step, you have your reproducible design.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.000
So looking at the layout,

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:58.000
to recreate the stack area chart,

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:03.000
which talks about how certain people were enslaved

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:08.000
from 1719 to 1870,

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:11.000
I used the original CSV file,

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:15.000
but the original file was laid out in a wide format.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:18.000
And when it comes to mapping software,

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:20.000
they don't usually want a wide format.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:23.000
What they usually want is a long format,

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:26.000
which means that they need a category column

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:29.000
as well as a value column.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:33.000
So I went ahead and changed the wide column,

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:36.000
the wide format, into a long format,

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:39.000
using the Pivot Longer from TidyR.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:43.000
So what this means is that they kept the year as it is,

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:47.000
and the function created two functions,

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:50.000
status for the category column,

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:52.000
and count for the value column.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:55.000
This makes it easier for multiple dimensions to show.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:57.000
And I also used the A package

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:00.000
to make the indentation and the structure nice.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:03.000
So now that we have the long format,

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:06.000
I could go ahead and create the stack area chart.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:10.000
Using ggplot, I used the year to plot the x-axis,

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:13.000
the count to plot the y-axis,

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:15.000
and the status to fill in the color.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:17.000
So to hard-code the color,

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:19.000
I used the Scale Fill manual

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:21.000
to use the black and green that he used

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:24.000
in the original plot.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:26.000
So continue with the layout.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:30.000
I used a somewhat complicated plot of his,

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:33.000
which has the US states,

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:35.000
the annotations, the narrative,

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:37.000
the legends, and the pie graph.

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:40.000
So this had to be broken down into one, two, three, four,

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:42.000
yeah, four pieces.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:45.000
The USA states, the pie graph,

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:48.000
the legends, and the annotations.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:50.000
So with the USA states,

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:52.000
there was a shapefile available,

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:57.000
but I felt like I wanted to create my own data CSV

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:00.000
to manually pick and choose

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:03.000
the colors each state represented.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:07.000
With the pie chart,

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:10.000
there was an original CSV file that was available

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:13.000
which showed the percentage of the professions.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:16.000
So what I did was I used the chord polar

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:20.000
to actually create the pie chart from the bar chart,

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:24.000
and I also had to color-code the professions.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:28.000
Using the ggforce package,

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:30.000
I used the geom circle

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:34.000
to create the circles to correspond to the professions.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:36.000
I used the ggforce package

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:39.000
because I didn't want to use the same ggplot package.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:41.000
Not that there's anything wrong with ggplot2,

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:45.000
but I just wanted to try something different.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:48.000
And with the annotate function,

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:51.000
I used to add the narratives

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:54.000
which comes under the theme element.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:56.000
And putting all these together,

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:58.000
the US states, the annotation,

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:00.000
the legends, the pie chart,

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:01.000
I used the cow plot.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:03.000
I thought the cow plot was a lot,

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:06.000
I found it was a lot easier to use.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:08.000
Instead of, there's nothing wrong with patchwork,

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:10.000
I just thought that it was easier

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:13.000
for everything to come out okay.

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:18.000
This was arranged using the plot grid function.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:20.000
Moving on to the color,

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:22.000
I mostly used the scale field manual,

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:24.000
as we saw earlier,

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:28.000
to try and match the colors used in the original plot,

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:31.000
which I think worked out very well.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:33.000
As for the topography,

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:35.000
that was in the narrative,

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:38.000
which is also an essential part of the design.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:40.000
When we talk about topography,

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:41.000
I'm talking about the styling

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:45.000
and the way it appears in the plot.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:46.000
I used the show text

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:48.000
so that it could appear on the plot,

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:52.000
and tried to find a number of fonts

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:54.000
using the Google font

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:58.000
so that the theme could show in the plot.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:03.000
After recreating the designs,

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:06.000
I found that there are a couple

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:09.000
of reproducible visual design principles

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:12.000
that I could follow to create a brand new visual.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:14.000
First is the intent.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:15.000
To follow the intent,

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:17.000
I looked at the purpose and understanding

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:19.000
of the original choices,

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:22.000
or what I wanted to do.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:23.000
They're the inputs,

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:26.000
which mean the visual elements,

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:29.000
the data, the font, the color, the narrative,

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:32.000
that are used to shape the design.

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:36.000
The structure, the layering of all the elements

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:37.000
that make up a graphic,

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:39.000
as we saw in the states,

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:42.000
the pie chart, and the annotation.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:46.000
The coding choices that you can use in any tool,

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:48.000
as in the quad polar that I used

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:50.000
to create the pie chart.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:52.000
You could also use...

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:54.000
What did I use?

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:55.000
There was...

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:57.000
Oh, the gg4, the gg...

00:10:57.000 --> 00:10:59.000
No, the geom circle,

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:02.000
as well as...

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:03.000
What was the other one?

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:04.000
I have to go back.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:07.000
Those are the coding choices I got to use.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:09.000
Of course, the fixed outputs

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:11.000
that come from the coding choices.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:13.000
Of course, the parameters can be changed

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:17.000
so that the different frames can come out differently.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:19.000
Of course, the shareability,

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:20.000
because they're all coded,

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:21.000
they're easy to share,

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:24.000
and they should be interoperable.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:26.000
Following these principles and the elements,

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:29.000
I thought maybe I can give it a crack

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:31.000
in another data visualization challenge.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:34.000
I chose the January Data Visualization Challenge.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:36.000
Has anyone heard of the January

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:38.000
Data Visualization Challenge?

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:43.000
It's actually a challenge that comes out every January.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:46.000
I started at the end of January.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:49.000
Actually, this challenge lets you use

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:52.000
algorithms to create artwork.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:54.000
When I started,

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:57.000
the daily theme was brutalism.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:02.000
Brutalism is an architectural design style

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:07.000
which comprises of raw material,

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:08.000
like concrete,

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:13.000
and it's not exactly ornamental.

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:14.000
It's just very structural.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:16.000
I had to think about,

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:21.000
since it's not a very ornamental design,

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:23.000
I had to make it interactive

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:26.000
for people to look at it better.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:30.000
That's why I used the principles.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:32.000
For the intent, I thought,

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:35.000
okay, maybe I can make it into an animation.

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:38.000
Instead of making it hard to look at,

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:42.000
I can make it interesting to look at.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:44.000
With the input,

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:47.000
I thought of using blocks and shades of gray

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:48.000
to keep to the original styling

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:53.000
and the theme of the style.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:55.000
Putting the structure,

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:56.000
I had to make sure

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:00.000
that the placement of the blocks changed

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:05.000
depending on whether they don't hit or not.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:08.000
What also mattered was the size.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:09.000
The size of the blocks,

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:11.000
they really do matter.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:13.000
Putting it in one plot,

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:15.000
I had to be careful of the clarity

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:16.000
and the proportion,

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:18.000
as well as the color.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:22.000
The coding choices had to do with the transition.

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:24.000
The transitioning of the blocks,

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.000
unfortunately, we won't get to see the code,

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:27.000
but at the end,

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:31.000
I'll show you a link to where you can see it.

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:33.000
As for the fixed outputs,

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:35.000
the length, the square frame, and the size

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:37.000
can also be changed

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:40.000
with the parameters

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:42.000
and the shareability,

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:46.000
the comment tools and the scripts provided.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:47.000
Then I thought,

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:49.000
well, since everything was okay

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:51.000
and working out all right,

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:52.000
with the recreation,

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:53.000
I think there's some things

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:56.000
that I could have done better.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:57.000
It was the color.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:13:59.000
As you saw earlier,

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:00.000
in my recreation,

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:02.000
I used a light yellow color

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.000
when I could have used the tan.

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:07.000
The tan could have looked a lot

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:10.000
like the original plots.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:12.000
As for the topography,

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:14.000
instead of trying to think of how

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:17.000
it could look just like the original,

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:19.000
I could have just used the topography

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:20.000
from the Dubois style

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:23.000
and picked out the public sands

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:26.000
and the charter.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:27.000
From there,

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:29.000
I don't think I would have changed

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:30.000
anything of the map,

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:32.000
but I do want to thank

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:33.000
my friends Gita,

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:34.000
Billy,

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:35.000
Miley,

