00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:04.000
If there are any questions,

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:06.000
you can ask them via Slido,

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:10.000
and I will be relaying them.

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:14.000
One question is,

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:17.000
does Dubois data exist electronically,

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:19.000
like in a package or a data set,

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:20.000
or do you have to create

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:21.000
the data set manually?

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:22.000
Oh, no.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:23.000
The data sets already exist,

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:26.000
and they're actually the original ones,

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:30.000
but some of them do come out

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:31.000
in the wide format,

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:33.000
so some of them do have to be changed

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:34.000
and in shape files,

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:37.000
so they all come from institutions,

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:38.000
from universities,

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:40.000
so they already exist.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:41.000
They're all there.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:42.000
They're not collected yet

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:43.000
in a single place.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:44.000
Pardon?

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:45.000
How do you mean?

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:46.000
They are not collected yet?

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:47.000
Oh, actually, for the challenge,

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:49.000
they are collected in a single place.

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:50.000
It's just that AJ Stock

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:52.000
had to collect everything,

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:54.000
so they originally come from museums

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:55.000
and institutions,

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:58.000
but you can all find them

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:01.000
in the Dubois GitHub repository.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:02.000
Wonderful.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:03.000
Thank you.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:06.000
Did you end up having to use

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:07.000
additional software,

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:08.000
for example,

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:09.000
Illustrator or Inkspace,

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:10.000
to polish up the designs

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:13.000
after creating the ggplot2 object?

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:14.000
No, not at all.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:15.000
I used everything in R.

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:17.000
I hardcoded it.

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:19.000
I didn't use any large language models

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:20.000
because this was done last year,

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:22.000
and because I'm from Africa,

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:23.000
we don't usually use

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:25.000
large language models yet,

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:26.000
so everything was hardcoded.

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:28.000
I googled everything.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:29.000
Yeah, so,

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:30.000
no, I didn't use any of it.

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:32.000
I just used R.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:35.000
Great.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:37.000
Do you think that an LLM

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:39.000
would be effective at writing code

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:41.000
to replicate these visualizations?

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:43.000
Using an LLM to recreate this?

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:44.000
I think it would be,

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:45.000
but you're going to have to

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:46.000
really guide it

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:49.000
because the layout is so different.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:50.000
It's unusual,

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:51.000
so you're going to have to tell it,

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:52.000
move this chart here,

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:53.000
move that map there,

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:55.000
move it up and down.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:56.000
It's possible,

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:58.000
but I think it would be easier

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:00.000
to do it yourself.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:02.000
Okay, wonderful.

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:05.000
We'll still be in for a job then.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:06.000
Yeah.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:09.000
Wow.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:10.000
All right, and with that,

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:11.000
I would like to, again,

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:15.000
thank Simzani for giving this talk.

